I.=E2=80=9D at every turn. Others insist that, actually, there were fewer g=
ood female contenders than in past years. Even some Republican women will a=
rgue that the talent bench isn=E2=80=99t there.

House Republicans have suffered the loss of formidable women in recent year=
s. Up-and-coming Republican women lost reelection=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s ho=
w Comstock, who was one of the more politically astute female members, left=
, as did Orange County=E2=80=99s Mimi Walters in 2018 and Michelle Steel th=
is year. Republicans also ejected two of their most prominent female member=
s=E2=80=94Liz Cheney and Jaime Herrera Beutler=E2=80=94for voting to
impeach Trump after the insurrection.

More are on the way out. Energy & Commerce chairwoman Cathy McMorris Rodger=
s is retiring, along with Kay Granger, who already gave up her Appropriatio=
ns gavel earlier this term. Elise Stefanik, the House=E2=80=99s No. 4 Repub=
lican, is headed to Turtle Bay pending confirmation as Trump=E2=80=99s U.N.=
 ambassador.

One gripe I heard today was that there has never been a female chair of the=
 N.R.C.C. That job=E2=80=94one of the most difficult and thankless in Congr=
ess=E2=80=94is filled by election of the entire conference and is often the=
 stepping stone to a choice committee gavel. Democrats, by comparison, will=
 have had a woman lead their campaign committee for three of the four most =
recent cycles.

Amid the angst, the Rules gavel is still in play, and Johnson hinted the di=
scussion is not over, saying at his news conference, =E2=80=9CStay tuned on=
 the final composition of chairs. We=E2=80=99ll see how it all shakes out.=
=E2=80=9D The
Rules slot is a quirky one: It=E2=80=99s chosen by the speaker and isn=E2=
=80=99t subject to term limits. Foxx, who=E2=80=99s termed out as chair of =
the Education and Workforce Committee, is making a bid for it, but she=E2=
=80=99s not currently on the committee, having given up her spot to run Ed.=
 There are surely current members at Rules who would be grumpy if she gets =
the nod.

None of this is a new problem for House Republicans. The gavel blackout is =
a downstream effect of 20 years of party recruitment practice. (Rep. Wagner=
 was a huge proponent of offering support to G.O.P. women 10 years ago, whi=
ch had mixed results.) It simply boils down to this: The many, many earnest=
 attempts to create a Republican counterpart to EMILY=E2=80=99s List pale i=
n comparison to the Democratic women=E2=80=99s group and its strength in th=
e Democratic Party. It=E2=80=99s long been the case that when EMILY=E2=80=
=99s List gets involved in a Democratic primary, it should be assumed that =
its endorsed candidate is a serious player, if
not the outright frontrunner. For a sense of scale, Democrats this term boa=
st 93 female House members, or nearly half of their caucus. Republicans hav=
e 34.

This has been a 40-year Democratic project, and the current slate of women =
in leadership in the House Democratic caucus=E2=80=94Katherine Clark as whi=
p, Rosa DeLauro at Approps, Maxine Waters at Financial Services, Suzan DelB=
ene=E2=80=99s two-cycle leadership of the D.C.C.C., and of course, the 20-t=
erm reign of Nancy Pelosi=E2=80=94is staggering in comparison to women=E2=
=80=99s positions in the House G.O.P. conference. Yes, Michigan=E2=80=99s L=
isa McClain replaced Stefanik in the fourth-ranking conference chair slot. =
But while there is Republican anger at their steering committee, the entire=
 leadership of the Democratic steering committee is female: Nanette Barrag=
=C3=A1n, Robin Kelly, and D.W.S. are co-chairs. Democrats aren=E2=80=99t in=
stalling women in important slots to
meet identity politics quotas=E2=80=94this has an organic feel because Demo=
crats have a deep bench of women to choose from, and they=E2=80=99ve been a=
round long enough to climb the ranks.

