          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Some Republican ins=
iders conceded to me, always with a sigh, that sexism is not only alive and=
 kicking in the House G.O.P. conference, but may have been given fresh life=
 by the party=E2=80=99s zeal for thwarting =E2=80=9CD.E.I.=E2=80=9D at ever=
y turn. Others insist that, actually, there were fewer good female contende=
rs than in past years. Even some Republican women will argue that the talen=
t bench isn=E2=80=99t there. <br/><br/>House Republicans <i>have</i> suffer=
ed the loss of formidable women in recent years. Up-and-coming Republican w=
omen lost reelection=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s how Comstock, who was one of th=
e more politically astute female members, left, as did Orange County=E2=80=
=99s <b>Mimi Walters</b> in 2018 and <b>Michelle Steel</b> this year. Repub=
licans also ejected two of their most prominent female members=E2=80=94<b>L=
iz Cheney </b>and<b> Jaime Herrera Beutler=E2=80=94</b>for voting to
impeach Trump after the insurrection.  <br/><br/>More are on the way out. E=
nergy &amp; Commerce chairwoman <b>Cathy McMorris Rodgers</b> is retiring, =
along with <b>Kay Granger</b>, who already gave up her Appropriations gavel=
 earlier this term. <b>Elise Stefanik</b>, the House=E2=80=99s No. 4 Republ=
ican, is headed to Turtle Bay pending confirmation as Trump=E2=80=99s U.N. =
ambassador. <br/><br/>One gripe I heard today was that there has never been=
 a female chair of the N.R.C.C. That job=E2=80=94one of the most difficult =
and thankless in Congress=E2=80=94is filled by election of the entire confe=
rence and is often the stepping stone to a choice committee gavel. Democrat=
s, by comparison, will have had a woman lead their campaign committee for t=
hree of the four most recent cycles.  <br/><br/>Amid the angst, the Rules g=
avel is still in play, and Johnson hinted the discussion is not over, sayin=
g at his news conference, =E2=80=9CStay tuned on the final composition of c=
hairs. We=E2=80=99ll see how it all shakes out.=E2=80=9D The
Rules slot is a quirky one: It=E2=80=99s chosen by the speaker and isn=E2=
=80=99t subject to term limits. Foxx, who=E2=80=99s termed out as chair of =
the Education and Workforce Committee, is making a bid for it, but she=E2=
=80=99s not currently on the committee, having given up her spot to run Ed.=
 There are surely current members at Rules who would be grumpy if she gets =
the nod. <br/><br/>None of this is a new problem for House Republicans. The=
 gavel blackout is a downstream effect of 20 years of party recruitment pra=
ctice. (Rep. Wagner was a huge proponent of offering support to G.O.P. wome=
n 10 years ago, which had mixed results.) It simply boils down to this: The=
 many, many earnest attempts to create a Republican counterpart to EMILY=E2=
=80=99s List pale in comparison to the Democratic women=E2=80=99s group and=
 its strength in the Democratic Party. It=E2=80=99s long been the case that=
 when EMILY=E2=80=99s List gets involved in a Democratic primary, it should=
 be assumed that its endorsed candidate is a serious player, if
not the outright frontrunner. For a sense of scale, Democrats this term boa=
st <i>93</i> female House members, or nearly half of their caucus. Republic=
ans have 34.  <br/><br/>This has been a 40-year Democratic project, and the=
 current slate of women in leadership in the House Democratic caucus=E2=80=
=94<b>Katherine Clark</b> as whip, <b>Rosa DeLauro</b> at Approps, <b>Maxin=
e Waters</b> at Financial Services, <b>Suzan DelBene</b>=E2=80=99s two-cycl=
e leadership of the D.C.C.C., and of course, the 20-term reign of <b>Nancy =
Pelosi</b>=E2=80=94is staggering in comparison to women=E2=80=99s positions=
 in the House G.O.P. conference. Yes, Michigan=E2=80=99s <b>Lisa McClain </=
b>replaced Stefanik in the fourth-ranking conference chair slot. But while =
there is Republican anger at their steering committee, the <i>entire</i> le=
adership of the Democratic steering committee is female: <b>Nanette Barrag=
=C3=A1n</b>, <b>Robin Kelly</b>, and<b> D.W.S. </b>are co-chairs. Democrats=
 aren=E2=80=99t installing women in important slots to
meet identity politics quotas=E2=80=94this has an organic feel because Demo=
crats have a deep bench of women to choose from, and they=E2=80=99ve been a=
round long enough to climb the ranks. <br/></td>
